==Events== * [[217]] &ndash; [[Roman Emperor]] [[Caracalla]] is assassinated. He is succeeded by his [[Praetorian Guard]] [[prefect]], [[Marcus Opellius Macrinus]]. * [[632]] &ndash; King [[Charibert II]] is assassinated at [[Blaye]] ([[Gironde]]), along with his infant son [[Chilperic of Aquitaine|Chilperic]]. * [[876]] &ndash; The [[Battle of Dayr al-'Aqul]] saves [[Baghdad]] from the [[Saffarids]]. *[[1093]] &ndash; The new [[Winchester Cathedral]] is dedicated by [[Walkelin]]. *[[1139]] &ndash; [[Roger II of Sicily]] is excommunicated. *[[1149]] &ndash; [[Pope Eugene III]] takes refuge in the castle of [[Ptolemy II of Tusculum]]. *[[1232]] &ndash; [[Mongol conquest of the Jin dynasty|Mongol–Jin War]]: The [[Mongol Empire|Mongols]] begin their [[Mongol siege of Kaifeng|siege on Kaifeng]], the capital of the [[Jin dynasty (1115–1234)|Jin dynasty]]. *[[1271]] &ndash; In [[Syria]], sultan [[Baibars]] conquers the [[Krak des Chevaliers]]. *[[1665]] &ndash; English colonial patents are granted for the establishment of the [[Monmouth Tract]], for what would eventually become [[Monmouth County, New Jersey|Monmouth County]] in northeastern [[New Jersey]]. *[[1730]] &ndash; [[Congregation Shearith Israel|Shearith Israel]], the first [[synagogue]] in New York City, is dedicated. *[[1740]] &ndash; [[War of Jenkins' Ear]]: Three British ships [[Action of 8 April 1740|capture]] the Spanish [[third-rate]] ''Princesa'', taken into service as {{HMS|Princess|1740|6}}. *[[1808]] &ndash; The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Baltimore|Roman Catholic Diocese of Baltimore]] is promoted to an archdiocese, with the founding of the dioceses of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York|New York]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia|Philadelphia]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston|Boston]], and [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville|Bardstown]] (now Louisville) by [[Pope Pius VII]]. *[[1820]] &ndash; The [[Venus de Milo]] is discovered on the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] island of [[Milos]]. *[[1832]] &ndash; [[Black Hawk War]]: Around three-hundred United States 6th Infantry troops leave [[St. Louis, Missouri]] to fight the [[Sauk people|Sauk]] [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]. *[[1864]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Battle of Mansfield]]: [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces are thwarted by the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] army at [[Mansfield, Louisiana]]. *[[1866]] &ndash; Italy and [[Prussia]] [[Austro-Prussian War|ally against]] the [[Austrian Empire]]. *[[1886]] &ndash; [[William Ewart Gladstone]] introduces the first [[Irish Government Bill 1886|Irish Home Rule Bill]] into the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|British House of Commons]]. *[[1895]] &ndash; In [[Pollock v. Farmers' Loan & Trust Co.]] the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] declares unapportioned [[income tax]] to be [[Constitutionality|unconstitutional]]. *[[1904]] &ndash; The [[French Third Republic]] and the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] sign the ''[[Entente cordiale]]''. * 1904 &ndash; [[Longacre Square]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]] is renamed [[Times Square]] after ''[[The New York Times]]''. *[[1906]] &ndash; [[Auguste Deter]], the first person to be diagnosed with [[Alzheimer's disease]], dies. *[[1908]] &ndash; [[H. H. Asquith]] of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] takes office as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], succeeding Sir [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Roy|authorlink=Roy Jenkins|title=Asquith|edition=Third|year=1986|publisher=Collins|location=London|isbn=0002177129|pages=179–180|chapter=An assured Succession 1908}}</ref> *[[1908]] &ndash; [[Harvard University]] votes to establish the [[Harvard Business School]]. *[[1911]] &ndash; [[Dutch people|Dutch]] physicist [[Heike Kamerlingh Onnes]] discovers [[superconductivity]]. *[[1913]] &ndash; The [[17th Amendment to the United States Constitution]], requiring direct [[election]] of [[United States Senate|Senators]], becomes law. *[[1916]] &ndash; In [[Corona, California]], race car driver [[Bob Burman]] crashes, killing three (including himself), and badly injuring five spectators. *[[1918]] &ndash; [[World War I]]: Actors [[Douglas Fairbanks]] and [[Charlie Chaplin]] sell [[war bond]]s on the streets of New York City's financial district. *[[1924]] &ndash; [[Sharia]] courts are abolished in [[Turkey]], as part of [[Atatürk's Reforms]]. *[[1929]] &ndash; [[Indian independence movement]]: At the Delhi Central Assembly, [[Bhagat Singh]] and [[Batukeshwar Dutt]] throw handouts and bombs to court arrest. *[[1935]] &ndash; The [[Works Progress Administration]] is formed when the [[Emergency Relief Appropriation Act of 1935]] becomes law. *[[1942]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Siege of Leningrad]]: [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] forces open a much-needed railway link to [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]]. * 1942 &ndash; World War II: The [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] take [[Bataan]] in the [[Philippines]]. *[[1943]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], in an attempt to check [[inflation]], freezes wages and prices, prohibits workers from changing jobs unless the war effort would be aided thereby, and bars rate increases by [[common carrier]]s and [[public utilities]]. *[[1943]] &ndash; [[Otto and Elise Hampel]] are executed in [[Berlin]] for their anti-Nazi activities. *[[1945]] &ndash; World War II: After an air raid accidentally destroys a train carrying about 4,000 [[Nazi concentration camp]] internees in [[Prussian Hanover]], the survivors are [[Celler Hasenjagd|massacred]] by Nazis. *[[1946]] &ndash; [[Électricité de France]], the world's largest [[utility company]], is formed as a result of the [[nationalisation]] of a number of electricity producers, transporters and distributors. *[[1950]] &ndash; [[India]] and [[Pakistan]] sign the [[Liaquat–Nehru Pact]]. *[[1952]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Harry Truman]] calls for the seizure of all domestic steel mills in an attempt to prevent the [[1952 steel strike]]. *[[1953]] &ndash; [[Mau Mau]] leader [[Jomo Kenyatta]] is convicted by [[British Kenya]]'s rulers. *[[1954]] &ndash; A Royal Canadian Air Force Canadair [[T-6 Texan|Harvard]] collides with a [[Trans-Canada Air Lines|Trans-Canada Airlines]] [[Canadair North Star]] over [[Moose Jaw, Saskatchewan]], killing 37 people. * 1954 &ndash; [[South African Airways Flight 201]] A [[De Havilland Comet|de Havilland DH.106 Comet 1]] crashes into the sea during night killing 21 people. *[[1959]] &ndash; A team of computer manufacturers, users, and university people led by [[Grace Hopper]] meets to discuss the creation of a new [[programming language]] that would be called [[COBOL]]. * 1959 &ndash; The [[Organization of American States]] drafts an agreement to create the [[Inter-American Development Bank]]. *[[1960]] &ndash; The [[Netherlands]] and [[West Germany]] sign an agreement to negotiate the return of [[Dutch annexation of German territory after World War II|German land annexed by the Dutch]] in return for 280 million [[German mark]]s as [[Wiedergutmachung]]. *[[1961]] &ndash; A large explosion on board the {{MV|Dara}} in the [[Persian Gulf]] kills 238. *[[1964]] &ndash; The [[Gemini 1]] test flight is conducted. *[[1968]] &ndash; [[BOAC Flight 712]] catches fire shortly after take off. As a result of her actions in the accident, [[Barbara Jane Harrison]] is awarded a posthumous [[George Cross]], the only GC awarded to a woman in peacetime. *[[1970]] &ndash; [[Bahr El-Baqar primary school bombing]]: Israeli bombers strike an Egyptian school. Forty-six children are killed. *[[1974]] &ndash; At [[Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium]], [[Hank Aaron]] hits his 715th career [[home run]] to surpass [[Babe Ruth]]'s 39-year-old record. *[[1975]] &ndash; [[Frank Robinson]] manages the [[Cleveland Indians]] in his first game as major league [[baseball]]'s first [[African American]] manager. *[[1987]] &ndash; [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] executive [[Al Campanis]] resigns amid controversy over [[Racism|racially charged]] remarks he had made while on ''[[Nightline]]''. *[[1992]] &ndash; Retired [[tennis]] great [[Arthur Ashe]] announces that he has [[AIDS]], acquired from [[blood transfusion]]s during one of his two heart surgeries. <!-- do not add Kurt Cobain's death. Deaths go in the death section, this one is listed on April 5 --> *[[1993]] &ndash; The [[Republic of North Macedonia]] joins the [[United Nations]]. *[[1999]] &ndash; [[Haryana Gana Parishad]], a political party in the Indian state of [[Haryana]], merges with the [[Indian National Congress]]. *[[2004]] &ndash; [[War in Darfur]]: The [[April 8 Humanitarian Ceasefire Agreement|Humanitarian Ceasefire Agreement]] is signed by the [[Sudan]]ese government and two rebel groups. *[[2006]] &ndash; [[Shedden massacre]]: The bodies of eight men, all shot to death, are found in a field in [[Shedden, Elgin County, Ontario]]. The murders are soon linked to the [[Bandidos Motorcycle Club]]. *[[2008]] &ndash; The construction of the [[Bahrain World Trade Center|world's first skyscraper to integrate wind turbines]] is completed in [[Bahrain]]. *[[2013]] &ndash; The [[Islamic State of Iraq]] enters the [[Syrian Civil War]] and begins by declaring a merger with the [[Al-Nusra Front]] under the name [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State of Iraq and ash-Sham]].
